The synthesis of MOFs based on flexible ligands is of current interest because flexible ligands may twist to make the MOF structures more versatile. In this work, the flexible polycarboxylic acid ligand 5-(bis(4-carboxybenzyl)amino)isophthalic acid (H4L), having two isophthalate and one benzoate group, connected through a triethylamine moiety, was selected as a functional ligand to construct luminescent Ln-MOFs. Two 3D lanthanide MOFs, namely {{Me2NH2}[TbIII(L)]·3H2O·DMF}
n
 (1) and {{Me2NH2}[EuIII(L)]·3H2O·DMF}
n
 (2), were prepared under solvothermal conditions. They were characterized and structurally determined. The microporous structures, as well as the confinement of cations inside the MOFs pores, allow the two Ln-MOFs to act as sensitive chemical sensors. In particular, we found that compound 1 is highly sensitive to the Fe3+ ion and NB molecule, indicating that the Ln-MOF can be considered as a dual-functional luminescent sensing material.
